[[File:Kuwayama-jinja ishitorii.JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Stone Torii}}{{small|Constructed in 1933. Mt. Mendori (Mt. Amaoka) is in the background. }}]]
'''Kuwayama Shrine'' (Kuwayama Shrine) is located in {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|qid=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Kameoka City|Q633996|qid=Q633996|1=Kameoka, Kyoto}}Kamiyada Town. In {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, {{ill|lt=Modern shrine rank system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=Old shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q134917326|lt=Fusha|1=Fu-sha}}. It is also commonly known as ``Yada-sha'' or ``Yada-miya''.

=== Overview ===
It is enshrined at the eastern foot of Mt. Menkoyama in the southern part of {{ill|lt=Kameoka City|Q633996|qid=Q633996|1=Kameoka, Kyoto}}. Many ancient ruins remain in the surrounding area, including Mt.

In the {{ill|lt=Kameoka Basin|Q11181997|qid=Q11181997|1=Kameoka Basin}}, which is said to have been a lake in ancient times, the enshrined deity {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Oomi Takamikoto (Ōkuninushi)|1=Ōkuninushi}} This shrine is based on the legend that, as part of the efforts to build the country, {{ill|lt=Hozu Gorge|Q10887680|qid=Q10887680|1=Hozu Gorge}} was excavated to create a basin, and the hoes used for the excavation were piled up here.

Within the fence of the precincts, Hachiman Shrine is built alongside the main shrine in the same size and style, and both shrine buildings are registered as {{ill|lt=List of Kyoto Prefecture Designated and Registered Cultural Properties|Q11375201|qid=Q11375201|lt=Kyoto Prefecture Registered Cultural Properties|1=Kyoto Prefecture Registered Cultural Properties}}. Many autumn leaves are planted in the precincts, and it is also a famous spot for autumn leaves. In addition, the annual festival ``{{ill|lt=Kameoka Festival|Q11370928|qid=Q11370928|1=Kameoka Festival}}'' is a traditional festival in Kameoka City, where people carry the gods to Kameoka City.

=== Enshrined God ===
* Kuwayama Shrine: '''{{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Ōmi Takamikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}''' (Onamuchi no Mikoto)
*: Okuninushi is the same as {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Ōkuninushi|1=Ōkuninushi}} and is an Izumo god. It is said to be the main deity that has been enshrined since its founding.
* Hachiman Shrine: '''{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Honda Beszon|1=UNKNOWN}}''' (Hondawake no Mikoto)
*: Honda Besson is the same as {{ill|lt=Emperor Ojin|Q317997|qid=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}}, and {{ill|lt=Hachimanjin|Q261637|qid=Q261637|1=Hachiman}}. It is said to be a guest deity that has been enshrined since the first year of {{ill|lt=Eiman|Q1193868|qid=Q1193868|1=Eiman}} ({{ill|lt=1165|Q19676|qid=Q19676|1=1165}}).
The divine crest of Kuwayama Shrine is a rabbit, in honor of Okuninushi no Mikoto, and that of Hachiman Shrine is a dove, as is customary.

=== History ===

=== Legend ===
[[File:Hozukyō (Kameoka).JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Entrance to the traditional site of {{ill|lt=Hozukyo|Q10887680|qid=Q10887680|1=Hozu Gorge}}}}{{small|{{ill|lt=Ukeda Shrine|Q11631810|qid=Q11631810|1=Uketa Shrine}} on the left bank, {{ill|lt=Kuwata Shrine #Kuwata Shrine (Yamamoto, Shinomachi, Kameoka City)|Q11537594|qid=Q11537594|lt=Kuwata Shrine|1=Kuwada Shrine}} is enshrined there. }}]]

==== Founding of Kuwasan Shrine ====
Regarding the founding of Kuwayama Shrine, there is a legend in the "Yada no Saiki" written in the first year of {{ill|lt=Enpo|Q1145735|qid=Q1145735|1=Enpō}} ({{ill|lt=1673|Q7617|qid=Q7617|1=1673}}). </ref>. According to this, in ancient times, Izumo Okami and Yagami colluded with Mt. Kurogara to develop the {{ill|lt=Kameoka Basin|Q11181997|qid=Q11181997|1=Kameoka Basin}}, which was a mud lake. He then rides an oak boat and cuts open the Uketa Gorge (currently the mouth of {{ill|lt=Hozu Gorge|Q10887680|qid=Q10887680|1=Hozu Gorge}}), and succeeds in draining the water in the direction of {{ill|lt=Yamashiro Province|Q749276|qid=Q749276|1=Yamashiro Province}}, thus creating a vast plain. Izumo Okami was enshrined at the foot of Mt. Amaoka and was revered as Kuwayama Daimyojin. Additionally, this god did not attend the October (Kannazuki) meeting in Izumo Province, but the eight gods in the county met at Kuwayama Shrine <ref name=chimei/>. It is also said that the name of the shrine was given to Kuwayama because the hoes used for excavation were piled up there. </ref> (Also see "{{ill|lt=Kameoka Basin #Lake Lore|Q11181997|qid=Q11181997|1=Kameoka Basin}}").

==== Hachimangu Shrine's solicitation ====
[[File:Kuwayama-jinja koike.JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|A small pond between Kuwayama Shrine and Hachiman Shrine}}{{small|It is said that it was established so that the two shrines would not fight each other. }}]]
Regarding the parallel Hachiman Shrine, it is said in "Yada no Saiki" that it descended to Mt. Menfuri (Mt. Amaoka) in the first year of {{ill|lt=Eiman|Q1193868|qid=Q1193868|1=Eiman}} ({{ill|lt=1165|Q19676|qid=Q19676|1=1165}}). Since then, it has been enshrined as Shin Hachimangu Shrine next to Kuwayamagu Shrine, but there were thunderstorms and fights between pigeons and rabbits. The villagers thought this was a discord between the two gods, and it is said that the conflict was resolved by moving Hachimangu Shrine to Sugitani <ref name=chimei/>. Although it is unclear whether this is related to the legend, Kuwayama Shrine currently uses a rabbit, and Hachiman Shrine uses a pigeon.

Even after both shrines were moved to their current location in {{ill|lt=Keicho|Q1328185|qid=Q1328185|1=Keichō}}14 ({{ill|lt=1609|Q6762|qid=Q6762|1=1609}}), a small pond was built between the two shrines to prevent conflicts, and the pond still exists today.

=== Outline ===
According to the shrine's legend, Kuwazangu Shrine was founded in the 2nd year of Wado ({{ill|lt=709|Q23514|qid=Q23514|1=709}}), and was originally located in Iou Valley, behind Mt. There are small shrines dotted all the way to the top of Mt. Menduri, and at the top of the mountain there is a shadow stone that is said to have descended from Hachimangu Shrine <ref name=kamigami/>. There are many ancient tombs in the surrounding area, and there is also a theory that there was a kokuga or a county seat based on the legend that a {{ill|lt=tunkura|Q11465761|qid=Q11465761|1=Miyake}} was established in the Miyake area, suggesting that Mt.

In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} from the middle of the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|qid=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, it is written as ``{{ill|lt=Tamba Province|Q954511|qid=Q954511|1=Tanba Province}}{{ill|lt=Kuwata District|Q11537600|qid=Q11537600|1=Kuwada district}} Kuwayama Shrine,'' and it is listed as {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q134917286|lt=Shikiuchi Shrine|1=Shikinaisha}}. It is said that the physician {{ill|lt=Yasuyori Tamba|Q1466794|qid=Q1466794|1=Tanba no Yasuyori}}, who was born in Iōdani, believed in Kuwayama Shrine, and the name ``Iōdani'' also came from Yasuyori, who was well versed in medicine.The place name ``Yada'' is related to Kuwayama Shrine, and there are 8 shrines: Otabisho, Rakuta, Yuuda, Hanada, Yokata, Sumoda, Babada, Zoyoda, and Hoshada. <ref name=yuisho>The shrine was called ``Hatta'' because it had </ref>, and later changed to ``Yada'' when {{ill|lt=Minamoto no Yorimasa|Q164948|qid=Q164948|1=Minamoto no Yorimasa}} received the shrine. </ref>. It is also said that festivals such as the mikoshi festival, eight-day festival, niwa kagura, horse racing, sumo wrestling, sarugaku, etc. have been held since ancient times. name=chimei/> invaded Tanba in {{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}}4 ({{ill|lt=1576|Q6700|qid=Q6700|1=1576}}) nk|Akechi Mitsuhide|Q313320}} abolished those festivals, and Daichi-in (currently an abandoned temple) was built as {{ill|lt=Bettoji|Q11396755|qid=Q11396755|1=Bettō-ji}}<ref name=chimei/>. Eight Kanda were also requisitioned <ref name=chimei/>.

{{ill|lt=Keicho|Q1328185|qid=Q1328185|1=Keichō}}14 ({{ill|lt=1609|Q6762|qid=Q6762|1=1609}}), {{ill|lt=Kameyama Castle (Tamba Province)|Q1037429|qid=Q1037429|lt=Kameyama Castle|1=Kameyama Castle (Kyoto)}} The lord {{ill|lt=Mori Okanabe|Q11473887|qid=Q11473887|1=Nagamori Okabe}} built a new shrine building at the current location and moved it, and also donated the shrine land <ref name=yuisho/>. In {{ill|lt=Kanei|Q1192913|qid=Q1192913|1=Kan'ei}}16 ({{ill|lt=1639|Q6897|qid=Q6897|1=1639}}), the domain of the shrine was donated by Sadafusa Suganuma, the lord of the domain <ref name=yuisho/>.In {{ill|lt=Enpo|Q1145735|qid=Q1145735|1=Enpō}} 9th year ({{ill|lt=1681|Q7645|qid=Q7645|1=1681}}), Morichika Sugihara wrote ``Festival Chukoki'' and revived the festival <ref name=chimei/>. In the same year, a mikoshi was donated by the castle lord {{ill|lt=Tadaharu Matsudaira|Q11069865|qid=Q11069865|1=Matsudaira Tadaharu}}<ref name=yuisho/>, and since then the annual festival has become popular as the Kameyama Festival (later Kameoka Festival), the largest festival in Kuchitamba.

{{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|qid=Q7757|1=1873}}) {{ill|lt=Modern company rank system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} It was ranked as {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} in 1998, and was promoted to {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q134917326|lt=Fusha|1=Fu-sha}} in {{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}3.

=== Precincts ===
[[File:Kuwayama-jinja kuwayamagū-2.jpg|thumb|180px|right|{{center|Kuwayamamiya}}]]
[[File:Kuwayama-jinja hachimangū-2.jpg|thumb|180px|right|{{center|Hachimangu Shrine}}]]
The main shrine, Kuwayamagu Shrine, and Hachimangu Shrine are located within the same fence, with Kuwayamagu Shrine on the left and Hachimangu Shrine on the right. Both shrines have the same format and size, and were built in the same year as {{ill|lt=Bunka (era name)|Q1373146|qid=Q1373146|lt=Bunka|1=Bunka}}11 ({{ill|lt=1814|Q6943|qid=Q6943|1=1814}}) of the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}. Kuwayama Shrine's {{ill|lt=ridge tag|Q8008834|qid=Q8008834|1=Munafuda}} exists since {{ill|lt=Kansho|Q1143928|qid=Q1143928|1=Kanshō}}3 ({{ill|lt=1462|Q6546|qid=Q6546|1=1462}}).

The style is Ikkensha {{ill|lt=Ryuzo|Q210684|qid=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}} and has {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=staggered gables|1=UNKNOWN}}. A one-room {{ill|lt=kara gable|Q977293|qid=Q977293|1=Karahafu}} shrine is attached to the front, and the roof is {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=persimmon thatched|1=UNKNOWN}}. Both shrines are registered as Kyoto Prefecture's registered cultural properties. </ref><ref>[http://spogaku.pref.kyoto.lg.jp/asset/1280.html Kuwayama Shrine Precinct Shrine Hachiman Shrine Main Hall] (Kyoto Prefecture homepage). </ref>.Based on the legend that Kuwayama Shrine and Hachiman Shrine were not on good terms, a small pond was built between the two shrines.

